{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"54762e3f-787a-4c80-891f-b6d02d1c903e","content":"I don't see the project file on disk, but here's how to configure it. Create (or edit) `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch the project.\n- Your server must read JSON-RPC from stdin and write responses to stdout (the standard MCP stdio transport).\n- Make sure your server does **not** write logs or other output to stdout — use stderr for diagnostics.\n\nAfter saving, VS Code will prompt you to **Start** the server. You can also manage it via the **MCP: List Servers** command.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"01351f4d-2d1e-41c1-a6f4-98100ee95104","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user says they built it. They're just asking for configuration guidance. I can answer this directly.","outputTokens":300,"requestId":"1588:3BD7C9:31B01AD:365D2DE:69FBE59C"},"id":"c55b794e-2cec-423b-8f73-f1d2b159ef6b","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:06:46.254Z","parentId":"735ebaff-3ad1-4008-b217-56c287164a47"}
